ter the flea bites, the blood test shows antibodies to a rickettsial antigen.","dimension":10,"group":5,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.12974,0.20411,0.16102,0.10089,0.074268,0.074385,0.056422,0.060876,0.043256,0.037642,0.030632,0.026763],"unified_progress":[0.11735,0.14282,0.11695,0.11015,0.087691,0.087517,0.071716,0.076689,0.060045,0.051128,0.043195,0.034749]},{"section":5,"text":"Hmm, so first, the key points here are the exposure to fleas and rats, the symptoms like fever and rash, and the antibody result pointing to rickettsia.","dimension":3,"group":8,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.082515,0.12732,0.1354,0.12412,0.10125,0.081237,0.072831,0.065255,0.056315,0.062996,0.046357,0.044398],"unified_progress":[0.082121,0.088847,0.091751,0.10281,0.098761,0.092256,0.090186,0.084262,0.075823,0.081648,0.062457,0.049074]},{"section":6,"text":"Rickettsial infections are often transmitted by arthropods like ticks, fleas, or mites.","dimension":8,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.045872,0.085878,0.099772,0.1086,0.11037,0.10416,0.097986,0.087009,0.0763,0.072882,0.059361,0.051813],"unified_progress":[0.055164,0.072205,0.092146,0.096033,0.10043,0.10705,0.098823,0.09482,0.086446,0.08075,0.064472,0.051654]},{"section":7,"text":"The classic ones I can think of are Rocky Mountain spotted fever, typhus, and maybe others like ehrlichiosis, but ehrlichiosis might not present with the same rash.","dimension":8,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.034832,0.07216,0.088118,0.10006,0.10571,0.1045,0.10316,0.09473,0.084829,0.086493,0.067813,0.057592],"unified_progress":[0.037641,0.062442,0.085231,0.096088,0.10091,0.10659,0.10406,0.10082,0.094138,0.09064,0.069888,0.051555]},{"section":8,"text":"The patient was in a rat-infested area.","dimension":11,"group":5,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.041102,0.078023,0.085381,0.09056,0.096013,0.10369,0.097658,0.095642,0.090447,0.08575,0.075598,0.060131],"unified_progress":[0.095825,0.11555,0.097587,0.089211,0.088023,0.08759,0.082795,0.085574,0.077716,0.071043,0.061133,0.047956]},{"section":9,"text":"Oh right, typhus is associated with fleas from rats.","dimension":8,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.035175,0.069749,0.082261,0.093189,0.10018,0.10455,0.1026,0.096933,0.08923,0.088207,0.074631,0.063299],"unified_progress":[0.074503,0.089085,0.10128,0.096377,0.094025,0.10053,0.091192,0.090439,0.079599,0.074567,0.060275,0.048128]},{"section":10,"text":"Epidemic typhus is from body lice, but endemic typhus (also called murine typhus) is from rat fleas.","dimension":8,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.028982,0.06357,0.079168,0.094524,0.10491,0.10849,0.10848,0.099267,0.088414,0.091529,0.07047,0.062196],"unified_progress":[0.03957,0.066028,0.096312,0.099261,0.10175,0.11092,0.1039,0.097951,0.089498,0.08163,0.063825,0.049344]},{"section":11,"text":"The timeline here: the incubation period for murine typhus is usually 7-14 days, which fits with the six days since the bite and then presenting with symptoms.","dimension":11,"group":5,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.048075,0.085945,0.087228,0.089056,0.092237,0.09635,0.094192,0.09321,0.086687,0.08486,0.075243,0.066915],"unified_progress":[0.067464,0.085242,0.086626,0.089671,0.092075,0.094674,0.090571,0.091929,0.086403,0.082223,0.072538,0.060585]},{"section":12,"text":"The rash that starts on the abdomen and spreads to the extremities is a classic description for Rocky Mountain spotted fever, but murine typhus can also have a similar rash.","dimension":8,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.044224,0.080278,0.084771,0.089766,0.094076,0.096234,0.096726,0.094133,0.087798,0.085773,0.075956,0.070264],"unified_progress":[0.052905,0.070947,0.085747,0.089514,0.093837,0.099994,0.0962,0.095619,0.090987,0.086451,0.075102,0.062698]},{"section":13,"text":"Wait, Rocky Mountain spotted fever is typically from tick bites, though.","dimension":8,"group":3,"is_degenerate":false,